479
00:20:23,922 --> 00:20:25,184
North.
<i>North,</i>

480
00:20:25,290 --> 00:20:28,691
<i>you will see</i>
<i>Monkey with Rash.</i>

481
00:20:29,094 --> 00:20:31,619
<i>The Egyptians used to set</i>
<i>their clocks by him.</i>

482
00:20:32,397 --> 00:20:34,957
<i>Oh look!</i>
<i>There goes an asteroid.</i>
Comet.

483
00:20:35,033 --> 00:20:38,002
<i>Comet! It's what they named</i>
<i>that cleaning solution after.</i>

484
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:40,436
<i>I know it may stink</i>
<i>when you leave it in the sink</i>

485
00:20:40,505 --> 00:20:43,497
<i>but, boy, oh boy,</i>
<i>does it clean!</i>

486
00:20:43,575 --> 00:20:45,566
Is there a reason
you're standing
so close to me?

487
00:20:45,644 --> 00:20:46,668
Just looking.

488
00:20:46,745 --> 00:20:48,212
Yeah, well, that's
the great thing
about looking,

489
00:20:48,280 --> 00:20:50,908
you can do it from
far, far away.

490
00:20:54,653 --> 00:20:56,678
<i>And now, ladies and gentlemen,</i>

491
00:20:57,322 --> 00:20:59,313
<i>I implore you to enjoy</i>

492
00:21:00,158 --> 00:21:03,457
<i>the majesty of the heavens.</i>

493
00:21:14,706 --> 00:21:16,867
(EXCITED MURMURING)

494
00:22:05,624 --> 00:22:06,613
Hey.

495
00:22:06,692 --> 00:22:07,784
You work here?

496
00:22:07,859 --> 00:22:11,260
No, I just happen to own
my own space suit.

497
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:12,319
(LAUGHING)

498
00:22:12,397 --> 00:22:14,729
A smart-ass.
I like that.
Get over here, kid.

499
00:22:15,100 --> 00:22:16,260
Do me a favor.

500
00:22:16,335 --> 00:22:19,361
Keep your finger
on the space bar
while I adjust this.

501
00:22:19,571 --> 00:22:21,038
Like this?
Uh-huh.

502
00:22:21,106 --> 00:22:22,368
You're gonna trust me
with this?

503
00:22:22,441 --> 00:22:25,001
I don't have
a lot of other options,
do I, space man?

504
00:22:30,682 --> 00:22:33,776
I gotta be honest.
This seems like
a job for two, no?

505
00:22:33,852 --> 00:22:34,910
Sometimes it is.

506
00:22:34,986 --> 00:22:36,544
But once
the scope is in place,
all you got to do

507
00:22:36,621 --> 00:22:39,146
is watch the monitor,
hoping to catch things
that nobody else has.

508
00:22:39,224 --> 00:22:40,851
You know,
if you got a partner,
you can switch off,

509
00:22:40,926 --> 00:22:44,157
you know, rest your eyes,
maybe make calculations
on what you've seen,

510
00:22:44,229 --> 00:22:47,824
or just break up the silence
of staring into the unknown.

511
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:49,992
So, where's your partner?

512
00:22:50,402 --> 00:22:51,994
Yeah, well that's
the bad part of it.

513
00:22:52,070 --> 00:22:54,368
He passed away
not too long ago.

514
00:22:54,706 --> 00:22:57,675
You know,
the Buddhists have
this saying about moving on,

515
00:22:57,743 --> 00:23:00,337
honoring the work...
But I don't remember it.

516
00:23:00,412 --> 00:23:04,246
What I do know is that
I realize I'm too old to be
doing this stuff all alone.

517
00:23:05,117 --> 00:23:07,551
So, you're
continuing the work, huh?

518
00:23:07,619 --> 00:23:10,611
Bryant would return
from the grave if I didn't.

519
00:23:10,722 --> 00:23:13,452
You know, we petitioned
for five years
for use of this scope.

520
00:23:13,525 --> 00:23:16,722
And we got lucky.
No, no, no.
No, no. Don't touch, no.

521
00:23:16,795 --> 00:23:19,662
I mean, once you get
in here, you gotta find
what you're looking for, fast.

522
00:23:19,731 --> 00:23:22,291
We had eight months.
Bryant saw six.

523
00:23:22,634 --> 00:23:24,226
Eight months seems like
a good chunk of time.

524
00:23:24,302 --> 00:23:25,826
Not in astronomy.

525
00:23:25,904 --> 00:23:28,395
See, once you find it,
you gotta track it.

526
00:23:28,473 --> 00:23:30,668
Okay? And then it's
not a discovery
until you chart it

527
00:23:30,742 --> 00:23:33,176
and then it goes around
again and then you prove it.

528
00:23:33,245 --> 00:23:35,145
Must get Ionely.

529
00:23:35,213 --> 00:23:36,737
I let you in
here, didn't I?

530
00:23:37,249 --> 00:23:40,514
Look, I just talk. You know?
I've got the gift of gab.

531
00:23:40,585 --> 00:23:43,179
Jeez, I'll talk
to anybody, I suppose.

532
00:23:43,255 --> 00:23:46,156
So, you still haven't found
what you're looking for, huh?

533
00:23:46,224 --> 00:23:50,593
No, but when I do,
you'll read about it,
believe me.

534
00:23:50,695 --> 00:23:51,923
You'll read about it.

535
00:23:52,063 --> 00:23:54,088
JESSICA: My real goal is
to become an astronomer.

536
00:23:54,166 --> 00:23:55,565
See something no one else has.

537
00:23:55,634 --> 00:23:59,434
I don't even need to make
a big, flashy discovery,
or name a star,

538
00:23:59,504 --> 00:24:01,404
or become famous like
most of these guys want.

539
00:24:01,473 --> 00:24:02,497
Yeah.

540
00:24:02,574 --> 00:24:04,940
All I've ever really
wanted is to know
I made a difference.

541
00:24:05,010 --> 00:24:07,570
That's great,
knowing what you want to do
since you were a kid.

542
00:24:07,646 --> 00:24:08,738
That's a gift.

543
00:24:08,814 --> 00:24:09,906
Thanks.

544
00:24:09,981 --> 00:24:11,380
You know,
you're a great
listener, Gus.

545
00:24:11,450 --> 00:24:14,783
Oh, well, it's easy
to talk to you, Jessica.
I mean, it's...

546
00:24:14,853 --> 00:24:16,115
Is something wrong?

547
00:24:16,188 --> 00:24:17,985
They've been in
there <i>4</i>5 minutes.

548
00:24:18,056 --> 00:24:19,114
So?

549
00:24:19,191 --> 00:24:20,749
It's a four-minute show.

550
00:24:20,826 --> 00:24:23,124
And that,
ladies and gentlemen,
is precisely why

551
00:24:23,195 --> 00:24:27,928
time travel is
not only possible,
but may have already happened.

552
00:24:32,437 --> 00:24:34,462
(ALL MOANING)

553
00:24:36,107 --> 00:24:37,938
(CHUCKLING NERVOUSLY)

554
00:24:38,543 --> 00:24:40,067
SHAWN: So, I met the
other astronomer.

555
00:24:40,145 --> 00:24:42,978
Nice guy. Chatty.
Hiding something.

556
00:24:43,048 --> 00:24:44,072
Something nefarious?

557
00:24:44,149 --> 00:24:45,878
I don't know yet.
How'd you do?

558
00:24:45,951 --> 00:24:47,976
Please, Shawn.
How do you think?

559
00:24:48,053 --> 00:24:50,248
(GASPING) Digits?
You know this.

560
00:24:50,322 --> 00:24:52,256
Nice!
We're going
out tomorrow.

561
00:24:52,324 --> 00:24:54,224
It's all coming
together, man.

562
00:24:54,292 --> 00:24:56,317
Juliet called.
She ran our dead
guy's phone records.

563
00:24:56,394 --> 00:24:57,486
We gotta meet her
at the station.

564
00:24:57,562 --> 00:24:59,257
You bet, let's go.
Whoa! Not now.

565
00:24:59,331 --> 00:25:00,889
5:00.
Why 5:00?

566
00:25:00,966 --> 00:25:04,367
Gus, I can't just
leave willy-nilly
whenever I want.

567
00:25:04,669 --> 00:25:06,296
I have a job to do here.

568
00:25:12,544 --> 00:25:15,513
I don't care what the
Coroner says. Healthy
hearts do not just stop.

569
00:25:15,647 --> 00:25:18,616
But you know what?
I got a golf buddy
who's a cardiologist.

570
00:25:18,683 --> 00:25:19,911
I'm gonna run
these by him.

571
00:25:19,985 --> 00:25:21,680
Mind the store,
I'll be back.

572
00:25:24,055 --> 00:25:26,285
(WHISPERING) Hey!

573
00:25:26,358 --> 00:25:30,158
Okay, so we ran the home,
the work, and the cell phone
records of Bryant Vallery.

574
00:25:30,228 --> 00:25:33,163
We got nothing
on the home phone, a few
strange hits on the work line,

575
00:25:33,231 --> 00:25:35,529
but when we ran
the cell phone,
we hit the jackpot.

576
00:25:35,600 --> 00:25:38,194
We found a number
that he calls, only
from his cell phone,

577
00:25:38,270 --> 00:25:40,636
all hours of the night,
way too often for business.

578
00:25:40,705 --> 00:25:42,434
Unless it's
monkey business.
Sweet!

579
00:25:42,507 --> 00:25:44,805
So we contacted
the cell phone company
for the name.

580
00:25:44,876 --> 00:25:49,609
The number is 555-019...

581
00:25:49,681 --> 00:25:51,148
Where is it?

582
00:25:56,855 --> 00:25:58,288
Oh, here it is.

583
00:25:58,356 --> 00:26:00,620
555-019...
Nine?

584
00:26:01,893 --> 00:26:03,292
Wow, that's good.

585
00:26:03,361 --> 00:26:04,692
Not really.

586
00:26:10,502 --> 00:26:13,266
SHAWN: So, she had an affair
with a married guy
and probably lied about it.

587
00:26:13,338 --> 00:26:14,396
That doesn't
mean she's guilty.

588
00:26:14,472 --> 00:26:17,066
Shawn, you're confusing me.
You're the one who loves
to jump to conclusions,

589
00:26:17,142 --> 00:26:18,166
and you're not
even hopping
towards this one.

590
00:26:18,243 --> 00:26:19,540
Hopping?
It doesn't track, Gus.

591
00:26:19,611 --> 00:26:21,306
Why would she kill him?
She broke up with a guy.

592
00:26:21,379 --> 00:26:22,676
It's him.
He dumped her.

593
00:26:22,747 --> 00:26:23,805
So, why doesn't she
mention to you

594
00:26:23,882 --> 00:26:25,349
that her ex-boyfriend
just bit the dust?

595
00:26:25,417 --> 00:26:28,045
What's she gonna say?
"Hey, how's it going?
My boyfriend just died.

596
00:26:28,119 --> 00:26:29,586
"He might have been killed.
Maybe it was me."

597
00:26:29,721 --> 00:26:31,245
(IMITATES CHORTLING)
I doubt she chortles.

598
00:26:31,389 --> 00:26:32,481
Damn, she was so
damn good-Iooking.

599
00:26:32,557 --> 00:26:34,889
And she still is, Gus.

600
00:26:34,960 --> 00:26:37,258
Even if we have a who,
we don't have a clear motive

601
00:26:37,395 --> 00:26:38,987
and we certainly
don't have the method.

602
00:26:39,064 --> 00:26:40,759
We can't give up
on our other suspects.

603
00:26:40,832 --> 00:26:41,924
What we need to do

604
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:42,989
(BEEPING)

605
00:26:43,068 --> 00:26:44,365
Is keep looking.

606
00:26:45,670 --> 00:26:46,728
You're gonna
set off the alarm.

607
00:26:46,805 --> 00:26:48,136
Clearly, I have
a security pass.

608
00:26:48,206 --> 00:26:49,366
They gave you
a security pass?

609
00:26:49,441 --> 00:26:51,432
They gave Dave
the cheddar corn guy
a security pass,

610
00:26:51,509 --> 00:26:53,443
I merely stumbled
upon it by happenstance.

611
00:26:53,511 --> 00:26:54,637
And by happenstance,
you mean?

612
00:26:54,713 --> 00:26:56,078
I swiped it
from his gym bag

613
00:26:56,147 --> 00:26:58,240
while he was shaking
a Milky Way loose
from the vending machine.

614
00:26:58,316 --> 00:26:59,874
Damn it! I...

615
00:27:00,752 --> 00:27:01,980
What are you
doing, Shawn?

616
00:27:02,053 --> 00:27:03,680
What I don't
have is a key.

617
00:27:03,755 --> 00:27:05,552
STALLINGS: That's not right.
What?

618
00:27:05,624 --> 00:27:07,091
I'm sorry.
I just... I...

619
00:27:07,158 --> 00:27:08,750
I left my pogo stick
in there and I just...

620
00:27:08,827 --> 00:27:10,192
No, I mean you're
not doing it right.

621
00:27:10,261 --> 00:27:12,661
You gotta move upward
if you wanna get the
latch to disengage.

622
00:27:12,731 --> 00:27:13,993
Let me do it.

623
00:27:14,666 --> 00:27:17,260
Uh... Don't you have
a key for that, or...

624
00:27:17,335 --> 00:27:18,324
For this room? No.

625
00:27:18,403 --> 00:27:21,429
Big bad Bryant took
it away a few weeks
after they got here.

626
00:27:21,539 --> 00:27:22,631
Why?

627
00:27:22,974 --> 00:27:26,466
A few small items go
missing and suddenly
everyone gets suspicious.

628
00:27:26,578 --> 00:27:27,806
Items such as?

629
00:27:27,879 --> 00:27:29,904
A watch. A comb. Some mail.

630
00:27:29,981 --> 00:27:31,005
Whose mail?

631
00:27:31,082 --> 00:27:32,811
The dead guy, Bryant.

632
00:27:32,884 --> 00:27:34,442
Did you read it?
Well, of course I did.

633
00:27:34,653 --> 00:27:37,816
You know, he became
quite a jerk. I don't know
if Hugo knows this or not,

634
00:27:37,889 --> 00:27:40,050
but he was dissolving
the partnership.

635
00:27:40,392 --> 00:27:42,826
Apparently, he had
some big plans for
himself. I don't know.

636
00:27:42,894 --> 00:27:46,330
Correspondence for jobs
he didn't seem qualified for,

637
00:27:46,398 --> 00:27:49,299
heading university
departments, NASA...

638
00:27:49,367 --> 00:27:50,629
NASA?

639
00:27:50,702 --> 00:27:52,294
Now. Who are
you guys again?

640
00:27:52,437 --> 00:27:54,803
We think something bad
went down in there.

641
00:27:54,939 --> 00:27:58,136
Yes, something bad
did go down in here.

642
00:28:00,011 --> 00:28:01,911
SHAWN: Did you
see anything?

643
00:28:01,980 --> 00:28:04,505
No. But you know,
the dead guy, he changed.

644
00:28:04,616 --> 00:28:05,640
They were friends
at the beginning.

645
00:28:05,717 --> 00:28:08,015
Hugo was always
being nice to him,
you know?

646
00:28:08,086 --> 00:28:11,055
In fact, Hugo's the only one
around here who's nice to me.

647
00:28:11,122 --> 00:28:12,953
Brings me coffee
in the mornings,

648
00:28:13,258 --> 00:28:15,089
although he brings
it for everybody,

649
00:28:15,493 --> 00:28:16,983
all four of us.

650
00:28:17,662 --> 00:28:18,686
Three of us.

651
00:28:18,763 --> 00:28:20,321
Stallings, I'll be
nice to you,
just do me a favor.

652
00:28:20,398 --> 00:28:22,263
Stop stealing the gum
out of my locker. Okay?

653
00:28:22,333 --> 00:28:23,322
(CHUCKLES)

654
00:28:24,335 --> 00:28:26,030
You spotted that?
Sure did.

655
00:28:26,104 --> 00:28:28,664
Hey, do you know
how these books work?

656
00:28:28,740 --> 00:28:32,904
Oh, they switch up
every couple of hours.
One looks, one writes.

657
00:28:32,977 --> 00:28:36,003
Yeah, they do it
from dark till dusk
all the time.

658
00:28:36,081 --> 00:28:37,378
Hugo's here.

659
00:28:37,449 --> 00:28:38,507
How do you know that?

660
00:28:38,583 --> 00:28:39,811
He gets here
at the same time
every day.

661
00:28:39,884 --> 00:28:41,681
You could set
your clock to it.

662
00:28:42,420 --> 00:28:45,082
Hey, you should hurry.
You don't have long.

663
00:28:45,156 --> 00:28:47,021
Thanks, dude.
Uh-huh.

664
00:28:51,329 --> 00:28:52,796
Gus, come check this out.
What?

665
00:28:52,864 --> 00:28:54,229
Look, there's a page missing
from this logbook.

666
00:28:54,299 --> 00:28:55,789
I noticed it
the first time I was here.

667
00:28:55,867 --> 00:28:57,027
Look.

668
00:28:58,036 --> 00:28:59,196
June 21st.

669
00:28:59,270 --> 00:29:00,464
GUS: What does
the book track?

670
00:29:00,538 --> 00:29:03,803
It's like Stallings said.
It's like, every manual
adjustment they make,

671
00:29:03,875 --> 00:29:05,570
who does it, which
guy was on the scope.

672
00:29:05,643 --> 00:29:08,237
See, it looks like they
switch shifts about
every two hours. Right?

673
00:29:08,313 --> 00:29:09,678
So, why remove this page?

674
00:29:09,748 --> 00:29:12,717
It goes from 8:39 with Hugo
to 10:<i>4</i>2 with Bryant.

675
00:29:12,784 --> 00:29:18,051
So the question is,
what happened between 8:39
and 10:<i>4</i>2 on June 21st?

676
00:29:18,123 --> 00:29:19,647
Some bad juju.

677
00:29:19,724 --> 00:29:21,191
We gotta get out of here.

678
00:29:21,459 --> 00:29:22,926
Why?
Why?

679
00:29:22,994 --> 00:29:26,122
Gus, someone finds
me in here,
I could get fired.

680
00:29:28,032 --> 00:29:29,829
Why do you keep
running like that?

681
00:29:31,503 --> 00:29:32,527
JESSICA: Hey, you guys.

682
00:29:32,604 --> 00:29:34,162
Hey. What's up?

683
00:29:34,572 --> 00:29:35,596
Gus, about tonight...

684
00:29:35,673 --> 00:29:37,607
Oh, if you have
other obligations,
that's cool.

685
00:29:37,675 --> 00:29:40,576
No, I just wanted to
see if we could go
at 6:30 instead.

686
00:29:40,712 --> 00:29:42,737
That's perfect.
That's even better.

687
00:29:42,814 --> 00:29:45,578
Look, I need to borrow
your motorcycle tonight.

688
00:29:45,650 --> 00:29:46,776
You can use
my little blue car.

689
00:29:46,851 --> 00:29:47,977
Oh, yeah!
Do that, Gus.

690
00:29:48,052 --> 00:29:49,952
I get a little nervous
on motorcycles.

691
00:29:50,021 --> 00:29:51,716
Settled! Bye, Jess.

692
00:29:51,790 --> 00:29:52,848
Bye.

693
00:29:58,163 --> 00:30:00,427
HUGO: Think you
want this one.

694
00:30:00,498 --> 00:30:02,466
What's that
in his case?

695
00:30:02,534 --> 00:30:04,263
Tracking readouts.

696
00:30:04,502 --> 00:30:07,369
Dude, it's just a bunch
of paperwork. I saw it
at the observatory.

697
00:30:07,438 --> 00:30:08,700
Why does he keep it
locked up like that?

698
00:30:08,773 --> 00:30:09,797
That's a
good question.

699
00:30:09,874 --> 00:30:11,842
Morning, gentlemen.
You up already?

700
00:30:11,910 --> 00:30:14,037
I had to check
the timers on
the crab spray.

701
00:30:14,112 --> 00:30:15,602
You need any help
with that giant thing?

702
00:30:15,680 --> 00:30:16,806
Nah, I can manage it.

703
00:30:16,881 --> 00:30:18,815
Only got two more weeks
of this before my time's up.

704
00:30:18,883 --> 00:30:21,078
Might as well follow it
through to the end.

705
00:30:22,654 --> 00:30:24,144
You know
what that means.

706
00:30:24,222 --> 00:30:25,450
I have no idea
what that means.

707
00:30:25,523 --> 00:30:27,855
That means he's
not at his house.

708
00:30:28,326 --> 00:30:29,554
So?

709
00:30:30,428 --> 00:30:32,828
SHAWN: Rainier's not exactly
a high roller, huh?

710
00:30:32,897 --> 00:30:33,955
GUS: No.
Look at that.

711
00:30:34,032 --> 00:30:36,262
It should say,
"Welcome to camp something."

