00:30:36,334 --> 00:30:37,699
Huh!

713
00:30:37,769 --> 00:30:40,203
Stargazing isn't the
most lucrative field.

714
00:30:40,271 --> 00:30:43,138
Well, you can make up to
a hundred grand a year on
the lecture circuit

715
00:30:43,208 --> 00:30:44,197
if you're a name.

716
00:30:44,309 --> 00:30:45,640
(GRUNTS)

717
00:30:47,579 --> 00:30:49,012
You're gonna break that.

718
00:30:49,747 --> 00:30:50,736
(GRUNTS)

719
00:30:51,649 --> 00:30:52,877
I don't think so!

720
00:30:54,986 --> 00:30:56,453
Whoa!
What?

721
00:30:56,654 --> 00:30:58,349
Oh, boy!

722
00:30:58,857 --> 00:31:01,792
What is this
awful purple stuff?

723
00:31:02,260 --> 00:31:03,318
They're flowers.

724
00:31:03,394 --> 00:31:04,622
Flowers?
It's a garden.

725
00:31:04,729 --> 00:31:08,358
It's a vegetable garden.
These are flowers,
weird flowers.

726
00:31:08,433 --> 00:31:09,730
What are you doing?

727
00:31:09,901 --> 00:31:10,890
Well, I gotta
check this out.

728
00:31:10,969 --> 00:31:12,061
Let Lassiter do that.

729
00:31:12,136 --> 00:31:14,434
Gus, Lassiter has
to come here on his own.

730
00:31:14,505 --> 00:31:16,598
And he has gotta be right.

731
00:31:16,674 --> 00:31:18,733
So, who you gonna get
to check that out for us?

732
00:31:18,810 --> 00:31:21,643
Well, who else do
you know who spends
all day in his yard?

733
00:31:21,946 --> 00:31:23,174
(GROANS)

734
00:31:23,781 --> 00:31:25,112
Shawn!

735
00:31:25,516 --> 00:31:27,484
Oh, you shouldn't have.

736
00:31:27,552 --> 00:31:29,520
Dad, we need to
talk business.

737
00:31:29,587 --> 00:31:32,021
You're not answering
your phone. What's going
on? Did you even check it?

738
00:31:32,090 --> 00:31:33,648
My phone's been fine, Shawn.

739
00:31:33,725 --> 00:31:35,124
I'm just a little
busy right now.

740
00:31:35,193 --> 00:31:36,854
Busy with what?
Things, Shawn.

741
00:31:36,928 --> 00:31:37,917
I have things.

742
00:31:37,996 --> 00:31:40,931
WOMAN: Henry, where
are the towels?

743
00:31:41,699 --> 00:31:44,259
Yeah, I'll tell
you in a minute.

744
00:31:44,936 --> 00:31:47,268
(STAMMERING) Was that a woman?
You have a woman in there?

745
00:31:47,338 --> 00:31:48,771
What do you think?

746
00:31:48,840 --> 00:31:50,671
Where did you meet a woman?

747
00:31:50,742 --> 00:31:51,731
Are you really interested?

748
00:31:51,809 --> 00:31:54,243
(STAMMERING) It's a question,
Dad. It's an enquiry.

749
00:31:54,312 --> 00:31:55,677
On the Internet.

750
00:31:55,747 --> 00:31:57,874
Shawn, look, she's
a very nice lady.
Her name is Sylvia.

751
00:31:57,949 --> 00:32:01,112
She runs a catering
business, has two kids.

752
00:32:01,853 --> 00:32:03,013
Would you like to meet her?

753
00:32:03,087 --> 00:32:05,282
Oh, God, no!
Are you kidding?

754
00:32:05,556 --> 00:32:07,547
Good. Can we pick
this up tomorrow?

755
00:32:07,892 --> 00:32:09,189
Yeah, I'd be glad to.

756
00:32:09,260 --> 00:32:10,420
Good.

757
00:32:13,698 --> 00:32:15,029
(EXCLAIMS)

758
00:32:18,102 --> 00:32:19,933
You must have thought
your Dad dated again.

759
00:32:20,004 --> 00:32:22,234
Honestly, Gus, I haven't
given it a lot of thought.

760
00:32:22,307 --> 00:32:24,104
It's been 15 years.

761
00:32:24,943 --> 00:32:28,504
Yeah, you know what?
It's fine. It's great.
Good for him.

762
00:32:28,646 --> 00:32:29,670
You wanna
talk about it?

763
00:32:29,747 --> 00:32:30,907
No.
Good.

764
00:32:30,982 --> 00:32:31,971
You left your plant there.

765
00:32:32,050 --> 00:32:33,347
I know.
Wanna go back
and get it?

766
00:32:33,418 --> 00:32:34,476
No.

767
00:32:34,852 --> 00:32:38,151
Okay, June 21st is
missing from the logbook?

768
00:32:38,222 --> 00:32:39,382
No, I'll check on
that right away.

769
00:32:39,457 --> 00:32:42,221
Sweet. So, does
Lassiter need any more help?

770
00:32:42,293 --> 00:32:44,386
No, Shawn, he is on fire.

771
00:32:44,462 --> 00:32:48,125
He's already had the autopsy
test rerun, and he's contacted
every relative he had.

772
00:32:48,199 --> 00:32:49,325
Is that a personal
call, O'Hara?

773
00:32:49,400 --> 00:32:50,458
Yes.
Wrap it up.

774
00:32:50,535 --> 00:32:52,867
I think I'm onto something.
I think he was killed
by someone he knew.

775
00:32:52,937 --> 00:32:54,427
I gotta go.

776
00:32:54,505 --> 00:32:57,599
Bryant Vallery opened
a safety deposit
box account in June.

777
00:32:57,809 --> 00:32:58,867
Was it around June 21st?

778
00:32:58,943 --> 00:33:00,035
What was June 21st?

779
00:33:00,111 --> 00:33:03,308
I don't know.
Didn't you say something
about June 21st yesterday?

780
00:33:03,381 --> 00:33:07,374
I've said so many things
in the last few days.
Refresh my memory.

781
00:33:09,954 --> 00:33:11,478
Dude, you look sharp.
Thank you.

782
00:33:11,556 --> 00:33:12,716
I've got one more
thing for you.

783
00:33:12,790 --> 00:33:13,950
What's that?

784
00:33:17,195 --> 00:33:18,355
You want me to wear a wire?

785
00:33:18,429 --> 00:33:19,987
Just this little
baby one.

786
00:33:20,198 --> 00:33:22,632
Look, in the event that
she actually did it, right?

787
00:33:22,700 --> 00:33:23,758
She's not gonna suspect you.

788
00:33:23,835 --> 00:33:26,201
Forget it, Shawn.
I'm gonna sit down with
her for 30 minutes,

789
00:33:26,270 --> 00:33:29,501
ask a few questions
and keep it cool,
just in case.

790
00:33:30,508 --> 00:33:32,135
Just in case she
didn't kill the guy.

791
00:33:32,210 --> 00:33:34,201
All right, here's
a compromise.

792
00:33:34,278 --> 00:33:35,506
Let me follow you.
No.

793
00:33:35,580 --> 00:33:38,310
Come on! From a
safe distance. It'll
be like, 30 yards.

794
00:33:38,383 --> 00:33:40,544
Consider me stealth, Shawn.

795
00:33:42,387 --> 00:33:44,048
Hey, be careful.

796
00:33:46,457 --> 00:33:48,687
You know, we have
a mirror in the bathroom.

797
00:33:49,627 --> 00:33:51,595
You seem jumpy.

798
00:33:51,662 --> 00:33:55,029
Me? Oh, no.
No, no. I'm excited.

799
00:33:56,634 --> 00:33:58,033
So...

800
00:33:58,536 --> 00:34:00,504
Tell me about
this guy you just
broke up with.

801
00:34:00,571 --> 00:34:02,835
Exes? Ooh!

802
00:34:02,907 --> 00:34:06,035
Don't you know the
number one rule of
first dates, Gus?

803
00:34:06,277 --> 00:34:09,303
I'm very comfortable
talking about anything.

804
00:34:09,514 --> 00:34:11,243
Well, there's not
much to tell, really.

805
00:34:11,315 --> 00:34:12,339
Mmm-hmm.

806
00:34:12,417 --> 00:34:14,112
About a month in,
I find out he's married.

807
00:34:14,185 --> 00:34:15,209
Right.

808
00:34:15,286 --> 00:34:16,446
Just my luck.

809
00:34:16,587 --> 00:34:18,179
And then he kept calling.

810
00:34:18,256 --> 00:34:21,020
He actually thought
I'd be okay with the
whole dirty scenario.

811
00:34:21,125 --> 00:34:24,492
He just...
He wasn't the guy I thought
he was, in a lot of ways.

812
00:34:24,595 --> 00:34:25,926
(CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)

813
00:34:25,997 --> 00:34:27,965
Wow, that's...
That's great.

814
00:34:28,032 --> 00:34:29,294
Why?

815
00:34:30,234 --> 00:34:31,701
I don't know.

816
00:34:34,472 --> 00:34:36,463
Hey, I'm sorry about
having to go earlier.

817
00:34:36,541 --> 00:34:38,600
It's just everything
changed at the observatory

818
00:34:38,676 --> 00:34:40,576
and I gotta get to work
early tomorrow, so...

819
00:34:40,645 --> 00:34:41,634
What's going on?

820
00:34:41,712 --> 00:34:44,180
Well, don't tell
anyone, but

821
00:34:44,916 --> 00:34:48,352
Hugo and Bryant may
have discovered a planet.

822
00:34:48,419 --> 00:34:49,977
Get out of here!
Yeah!

823
00:34:50,054 --> 00:34:52,284
An extra-solar planet.

824
00:34:52,557 --> 00:34:54,081
About six months ago, I think.

825
00:34:54,158 --> 00:34:55,819
Bryant kinda clued me in
the night they found it.

826
00:34:55,893 --> 00:34:57,485
He was so excited.

827
00:34:57,562 --> 00:35:00,224
They had to track their
data, wait for the planet
to come around again

828
00:35:00,298 --> 00:35:01,287
and complete its orbit.
Right.

829
00:35:01,399 --> 00:35:03,060
So, it must be verified now.

830
00:35:03,134 --> 00:35:05,568
I mean, you don't
just call a press conference
for nothing, right?

831
00:35:05,636 --> 00:35:07,695
Hugo is over the moon.

832
00:35:07,772 --> 00:35:10,002
Yeah, he's gonna
be famous forever.

833
00:35:11,375 --> 00:35:14,811
Do you have any idea
how huge this is for
someone's career?

834
00:35:14,879 --> 00:35:17,074
Um...
Of course he does.

835
00:35:17,381 --> 00:35:19,645
Shawn?
I was in stealth mode!
How did you find me?

836
00:35:19,717 --> 00:35:21,082
You knew he was
following you?

837
00:35:21,152 --> 00:35:22,176
No, not at all.

838
00:35:22,253 --> 00:35:23,447
Jessica, this is
a good thing.

839
00:35:23,521 --> 00:35:25,216
It means we don't
suspect you anymore.

840
00:35:25,289 --> 00:35:27,257
"We"? Suspect me of what?

841
00:35:27,325 --> 00:35:28,883
I didn't think you
killed him, Jessica.
Killed?

842
00:35:28,960 --> 00:35:30,825
And I hope this
doesn't create trust
issues for our future.

843
00:35:30,895 --> 00:35:32,192
We just needed to
establish motive.

844
00:35:32,263 --> 00:35:34,128
Dude, we totally
established motive!

845
00:35:34,198 --> 00:35:37,099
Well, congratulations,
Gus, whatever you are.

846
00:35:37,168 --> 00:35:40,865
You've got your motive,
whatever that is, but you
no longer have a date.

847
00:35:40,938 --> 00:35:42,530
No.
SHAWN: Jessie!

848
00:35:43,541 --> 00:35:44,838
(GRUNTS)

849
00:35:46,377 --> 00:35:48,038
Jessica, hold on a sec!

850
00:35:48,779 --> 00:35:49,973
Gus!

851
00:35:51,449 --> 00:35:53,144
Man, that's twice!

852
00:35:59,857 --> 00:36:02,291
...and to the Santa Barbara
Space Center

853
00:36:02,360 --> 00:36:04,260
for the use of
their facility.

854
00:36:04,328 --> 00:36:08,094
I dedicate this to
my departed comrade,
Bryant Vallery.

855
00:36:08,232 --> 00:36:09,256
(ALL CLAMORING)
Professor! Professor!

856
00:36:09,333 --> 00:36:10,630
When was the discovery made?

857
00:36:10,701 --> 00:36:12,430
The 21st of June,

858
00:36:12,737 --> 00:36:17,197
9:55 p.m., during a routine
changeover between
my partner and myself.

859
00:36:17,275 --> 00:36:19,140
While readjusting
some coordinates,

860
00:36:19,210 --> 00:36:24,113
I inadvertently made
what is certainly
the discovery of my lifetime.

861
00:36:24,315 --> 00:36:26,749
Which one of you
made the actual discovery?

862
00:36:26,817 --> 00:36:29,308
It was me.
We traded off chairs
every two hours.

863
00:36:29,387 --> 00:36:30,445
This was completely
by accident.

864
00:36:30,521 --> 00:36:33,354
WOMAN: What about a book?
Surely you'll have
a lot of book offers.

865
00:36:33,424 --> 00:36:34,516
(WHISPERING) Gus, you
know what this means?

866
00:36:34,592 --> 00:36:36,389
It's murder.
It's...

867
00:36:36,961 --> 00:36:38,792
No, it's motive.

868
00:36:38,930 --> 00:36:40,158
That's what I said.

869
00:36:40,231 --> 00:36:41,493
No, you said,
"It's murder."

870
00:36:41,566 --> 00:36:43,363
It's the same thing.
Motive, murder,
it's the same thing.

871
00:36:43,434 --> 00:36:44,696
No, motive is the
reason for doing it.

872
00:36:44,769 --> 00:36:45,895
It's in the same
family, Shawn.

873
00:36:45,970 --> 00:36:47,267
Shh! Shh!
HUGO: Now, this planet

874
00:36:47,338 --> 00:36:49,602
has everything required
for an Earth-like structure.

875
00:36:49,674 --> 00:36:52,768
It has proximity,
it has the right orbit,

876
00:36:52,877 --> 00:36:55,004
(CELL PHONE RINGS)
It has its own
energy source...

877
00:36:55,112 --> 00:36:56,545
You've got to change
that phone setting.

878
00:36:56,614 --> 00:36:58,343
(SIGHING) Jeez. Hello.

879
00:36:58,416 --> 00:37:00,646
Shawn, what the hell
do you think you're doing?

880
00:37:00,718 --> 00:37:03,278
Look, Dad, I can't talk
to you about your love life,
okay? I can't do it.

881
00:37:03,487 --> 00:37:04,613
My love life?
You still on that?

882
00:37:04,689 --> 00:37:07,249
I'm talking about this
foxglove you left on my porch.

883
00:37:07,325 --> 00:37:08,349
Foxglove?

884
00:37:08,426 --> 00:37:11,122
Your little plant with
the dirty roots. It's all
over my welcome mat.

885
00:37:11,195 --> 00:37:13,288
That was foxglove?
What the hell is foxglove?

886
00:37:13,364 --> 00:37:15,059
<i>Some neighbor's cat</i>
<i>could have wandered in,</i>

887
00:37:15,132 --> 00:37:17,566
chewed on it and croaked
right in my front yard, Shawn.

888
00:37:17,635 --> 00:37:20,263
Some foxglove has
a chemical called
digitalis in its leaves.

889
00:37:20,338 --> 00:37:21,965
What, is it, like, poison?
It's a medicine!

890
00:37:22,039 --> 00:37:24,473
And you know how I feel
about dead things in my yard.

891
00:37:24,542 --> 00:37:25,702
Look, Dad,
I'm sorry. I gotta go,

892
00:37:25,776 --> 00:37:27,641
I can't have two people
solving my case at once.

893
00:37:27,712 --> 00:37:29,543
Shawn, we should talk.
(SIGHING) Okay, fine.

894
00:37:29,614 --> 00:37:31,377
I'll be at Tom Blair's Pub
on Friday. Come by.

895
00:37:31,449 --> 00:37:33,940
I got a date on Friday.
Can you do Saturday?

896
00:37:34,018 --> 00:37:35,246
Never mind.

897
00:37:35,620 --> 00:37:37,349
Digitalis is prescribed
for heart conditions.

898
00:37:37,421 --> 00:37:38,581
I don't see how
that helps us, Gus.

899
00:37:38,656 --> 00:37:41,090
It can cause toxicity
in someone who doesn't
have a heart problem.

900
00:37:41,158 --> 00:37:42,250
Wouldn't that show up
in the autopsy?

901
00:37:42,326 --> 00:37:44,556
That's the problem.
You have to test
for digitalis specifically.

902
00:37:44,629 --> 00:37:47,223
No one would consider it
if someone doesn't have
a history of heart problems.

903
00:37:47,298 --> 00:37:48,287
Shh!

904
00:37:50,067 --> 00:37:51,125
Hey, what are
you doing here?

905
00:37:51,202 --> 00:37:53,329
We just got our
motive for murder,
Spencer.

906
00:37:53,404 --> 00:37:56,703
Hugo found out that Vallery
was gonna take all the credit
for their discovery himself.

907
00:37:56,774 --> 00:37:58,537
Cut him out of it entirely.

908
00:37:58,609 --> 00:38:00,975
Because he was
on the scope when
they made the find?

909
00:38:01,045 --> 00:38:02,740
Yes. Maybe.

910
00:38:03,281 --> 00:38:04,270
What are you doing here?

911
00:38:04,348 --> 00:38:05,440
Well, we heard
you had the motive,

912
00:38:05,516 --> 00:38:07,313
so we rushed down here
to volunteer our services.

913
00:38:07,385 --> 00:38:08,909
Thanks, but I'll take
this one myself.

914
00:38:08,986 --> 00:38:11,113
Okay, well at least
tell me about the poison.

915
00:38:11,188 --> 00:38:13,213
What poison? I didn't
say anything about poison.

916
00:38:13,291 --> 00:38:14,622
You most certainly did.
I heard it.

917
00:38:14,692 --> 00:38:16,853
Clear as day.
Must have slipped out.

918
00:38:16,927 --> 00:38:20,158
I have been thinking
about poison as a method,
but I can't figure out how.

919
00:38:20,231 --> 00:38:22,597
Would you like me to
read your innermost thoughts?

920
00:38:22,667 --> 00:38:24,897
Like deep, deep, deep ones.

921
00:38:26,671 --> 00:38:27,968
Knock yourself out.

922
00:38:28,039 --> 00:38:30,371
Okay, I just
want you to relax.

923
00:38:30,441 --> 00:38:32,102
Breathe normally.
Close your eyes.

924
00:38:34,011 --> 00:38:35,308
(EXHALES)

925
00:38:35,446 --> 00:38:37,471
Can you feel it? Can... Can...

926
00:38:37,815 --> 00:38:38,975
(GRUNTING)

927
00:38:40,718 --> 00:38:42,583
You want to check
the house, Hugo's house.

928
00:38:42,653 --> 00:38:44,587
(MUFFLED) I am in the process
of getting a warrant.

929
00:38:44,655 --> 00:38:45,713
What did he say?

930
00:38:45,790 --> 00:38:47,758
He's in the process
of getting a warrant now.

931
00:38:47,825 --> 00:38:49,554
The garden, check the garden.

932
00:38:49,627 --> 00:38:50,651
It's buried there?

933
00:38:50,728 --> 00:38:52,252
Something's growing.

934
00:38:52,763 --> 00:38:55,664
Oh, I'm getting something.
I'm getting...
I'm getting...

935
00:38:55,833 --> 00:38:57,824
Oh, oh, oh... Prince!

936
00:38:58,035 --> 00:38:59,127
No.

937
00:38:59,670 --> 00:39:01,194
The artist formerly
known as Prince.

938
00:39:01,272 --> 00:39:02,261
(GRUNTS)

939
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:03,466
Shawn! Wrong again.

940
00:39:03,541 --> 00:39:08,672
It's Prince after he was
known as "the artist
formerly known as Prince."

941
00:39:09,113 --> 00:39:10,307
It's purple.
Yes!

942
00:39:10,381 --> 00:39:12,281
Yes! That's it!
You're amazing.

943
00:39:12,350 --> 00:39:15,376
Oh, the caverns
of knowledge
in that thing.

944
00:39:15,820 --> 00:39:18,448
Here's the problem.
We ran the toxicology report.

945
00:39:18,522 --> 00:39:19,921
There's no trace of poisoning.

946
00:39:19,990 --> 00:39:22,515
Of course.
Thank you, Detective.

947
00:39:22,593 --> 00:39:26,791
So what you're saying is,
he would've had to administer
it very, very slowly.

948
00:39:26,864 --> 00:39:29,355
Yes. That's exactly
what I'm saying.

949
00:39:30,868 --> 00:39:32,563
How do you poison
someone slowly?

950
00:39:34,572 --> 00:39:37,370
<i>He brings me coffee.</i>
<i>Although, he brings it</i>
<i>for everybody.</i>

951
00:39:37,441 --> 00:39:40,205
<i>All four of us. Three of us.</i>

952
00:39:41,245 --> 00:39:42,872
Coffee.
No, I'm good.

953
00:39:42,947 --> 00:39:44,073
Tea.
Well, if you're going.

954
00:39:44,148 --> 00:39:46,639
It had to be the tea.
The leaves wouldn't
stand out in the tea.

955
00:39:46,717 --> 00:39:47,706
Hugo poisoned his tea.

956
00:39:47,785 --> 00:39:49,252
Every day for six months.

957
00:39:49,320 --> 00:39:51,185
Digitalis would cause
arrhythmia in a healthy heart.

958
00:39:51,255 --> 00:39:53,223
Which would disappear
as soon as someone died.

959
00:39:53,290 --> 00:39:54,484
Solved it!
SHAWN: No, you didn't.

960
00:39:54,558 --> 00:39:56,355
Yes, I did. Yes, I did.
No, you didn't.

961
00:39:56,427 --> 00:39:58,418
Oh, that's right.
You did.

962
00:39:58,496 --> 00:40:02,830
O'Hara, call the Coroner.
Tell him to check for even the
slightest traces of digitalis.

963
00:40:04,502 --> 00:40:06,970
And get me a new
pair of handcuffs.

964
00:40:12,810 --> 00:40:14,368
I've gotta be off.

965
00:40:14,445 --> 00:40:15,912
(ALL CLAMORING)

966
00:40:22,286 --> 00:40:23,651
CARLTON: Hi. Thank you.

967
00:40:24,588 --> 00:40:25,577
Thanks.

968
00:40:26,791 --> 00:40:28,053
Just part of the job.

969
00:40:28,392 --> 00:40:31,293
Spencer, a moment
of your precious time.

970
00:40:33,864 --> 00:40:35,559
Are you sure
we should be in here?

971
00:40:35,633 --> 00:40:37,123
That night in the bar,

972
00:40:37,735 --> 00:40:39,999
I mentioned
my wife, didn't I?

973
00:40:40,171 --> 00:40:41,934
Yes.
Oh, crap.

974
00:40:42,306 --> 00:40:43,603
What did I say, exactly?

975
00:40:43,674 --> 00:40:44,800
That she wants you back.

976
00:40:44,875 --> 00:40:46,672
No, no, I don't
think I said that.

977
00:40:46,744 --> 00:40:47,870
Maybe I sensed that.

978
00:40:47,945 --> 00:40:51,005
You didn't sense it either,
but thanks for trying to help.

979
00:40:52,082 --> 00:40:55,643
To tell you the truth,
I think I got some help
on this case.

980
00:40:56,754 --> 00:40:58,381
Really?
Yeah.

981
00:40:58,756 --> 00:41:00,553
Well, hey, man,
we all get help
sometimes, right?

982
00:41:00,624 --> 00:41:03,354
It's the truly great
ones that know
how to accept it.

983
00:41:03,427 --> 00:41:07,124
And if I may add one
more thing, Detective,

984
00:41:07,264 --> 00:41:08,925
you astound me.

985
00:41:09,233 --> 00:41:10,393
Second half to that joke?

986
00:41:10,468 --> 00:41:12,095
No.
No?

987
00:41:12,169 --> 00:41:13,898
The press is asking
for you outside.

988
00:41:13,971 --> 00:41:16,337
Tell them I will
be right there.

989
00:41:17,041 --> 00:41:21,341
To tell you the truth,
Spencer, sometimes
I astound myself.

990
00:41:21,412 --> 00:41:22,538
How's the knot?
Tight.

991
00:41:22,613 --> 00:41:23,807
Great.

992
00:41:24,181 --> 00:41:26,376
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

993
00:41:38,362 --> 00:41:39,659
All alone, huh?

994
00:41:39,730 --> 00:41:41,755
That would appear
to be the case.

995
00:41:41,832 --> 00:41:44,062
It's a Friday night.
What happened to Sylvia?

996
00:41:45,302 --> 00:41:48,499
Would you believe
that I didn't want to
hurt your feelings?

997
00:41:50,808 --> 00:41:52,833
Sit down. Have a drink.

998
00:41:56,514 --> 00:41:57,674
(SIGHS)

999
00:42:00,184 --> 00:42:01,446
You buying?

1000
00:42:03,087 --> 00:42:04,384
You kidding?

1001
00:42:13,831 --> 00:42:17,392
<i>In between the lines</i>
<i>there's a lot of obscurity</i>

1002
00:42:17,535 --> 00:42:20,868
<i>I'm not inclined</i>
<i>to resign to maturity</i>

1003
00:42:20,938 --> 00:42:24,271
<i>If it's all right</i>
<i>then you're all wrong</i>

1004
00:42:24,408 --> 00:42:27,866
<i>But why bounce around</i>
<i>to the same damn song?</i>

1005
00:42:28,946 --> 00:42:32,905
<i>You'd rather run</i>
<i>when you can't crawl</i>

1006
00:42:35,185 --> 00:42:38,814
<i>I know, you know</i>
<i>That I'm not telling the truth</i>

1007
00:42:38,889 --> 00:42:42,120
<i>I know, you know</i>
<i>They just don't have any proof</i>

1008
00:42:42,192 --> 00:42:45,184
<i>Embrace the deception</i>
<i>Learn how to bend</i>

1009
00:42:45,296 --> 00:42:49,198
<i>Your worst inhibitions</i>
<i>tend to psych you out</i>
<i>in the end</i>

1010
00:42:49,333 --> 00:42:51,392
<i>I know, you know</i>

1011
00:42:52,736 --> 00:42:54,465
<i>I know, you know</i>

